posts.name: Jared Van Horn
posts.cooked: Is the Orange Pi 5 limited to just 2 cameras? What limits the amount of cameras the Orange Pi can run with?

posts.name: Joseph Walters
posts.cooked:
Processing power and camera hardware interfaces (camera bus connectors, USB ports, etcâ€¦)

I canâ€™t link to it at the moment but 6328 mechanical advantage found running two cameras at higher frame rates and resolution was fine. Adding a 3rd started to slow all of them down in FPS, but depending on your application/tolerance that could still be acceptable.

posts.name: AfterTen
posts.cooked: The PhotoVision people also recommend only 2 camera per Orange Pi 5.

posts.name: Dan Katzuv
posts.cooked: You can run 2 cameras for AprilTags and another one for object detection. The latter uses the RKNN NPU so it has no drawback on AprilTags processing which uses the CPU.

posts.name: Anand Rajamani
posts.cooked:
This is my preferred setup. 2 tag detection cameras running 2 threads each, plus an object detection or driver camera. Or do 1 tag detection, 1 object detection, and 1 driver cam. The latter setup has some test data here: Beta Testing - Photonvision 2024 - Google Docs

Running 2 tag detection cameras will get you around 30fps on both with an OV9281 on 1280x720 Dec. 2, and you should be able to run object detection or a driver cam on top of that without getting slower.

posts.name: Jonah Bonner
posts.cooked:
Jwal:

6328 mechanical advantage found running two cameras at higher frame rates and resolution was fine

In fact, we found that running two cameras significantly lowered our frame rate compared to one per board. At 1600x1200, we could run 1 camera at ~40-45 FPS and 2 cameras at ~20-25 FPS. We switched to 2 cameras per board in 2024 because the lower frame rate was still acceptable and it significantly simplified wiring, but we definitely sacrificed some performance to achieve that.

posts.name: Anand Rajamani
posts.cooked: Was this with Northstar or Photonvision?

posts.name: Jonah Bonner
posts.cooked: That data is from Northstar, using the median frame rate during actual match play.

posts.name: Anand Rajamani
posts.cooked: I donâ€™t know how Northstar works, but does it multi thread or force tasks to run on different threads? This might be why youâ€™re seeing very different multicam performance vs PV (which the average team is more likely to use).

posts.name: Jonah Bonner
posts.cooked: The two cameras are running in entirely isolated processes, though we donâ€™t lock them to specific cores or anything like that. I think the performance difference weâ€™re seeing (~25 FPS with x2 1600x1200 cameras vs ~30 FPS with x2 1280x720 cameras) is a similar difference as weâ€™ve seen previously when comparing Aruco and PhotonVision/AprilTag3 detection on a single camera.

posts.name: Anand Rajamani
posts.cooked: Iâ€™m not as worried about the specific performance as I am about the drop. You note that 2 cameras runs about half as fast a 1 camera with Northstar, but I see closer to a 20-30% drop on PV when running standard Apriltag mode.

posts.name: Jonah Bonner
posts.cooked:
There are so many variables here that establishing why the relative performance is different is probably not particularly informative. Northstar and PhotonVision use different setups for decoding and processing frames, and weâ€™re comparing cameras running at very different resolutions. Since our benchmarks involve more than 2x the number of pixels per frame, an alternative benchmark may be comparing 2 vs 4 cameras with PhotonVision (though of course thatâ€™s not quite representative either given all of the other differences).

Regardless, we maintain that 1) we donâ€™t use Northstar because of performance and 2) PhotonVision is a better choice for almost all teams. I just wanted to correct the notion that 6328 has data showing equivalent performance with 1 and 2 cameras, since we only switched to multiple cameras per Pi to simplify the overall system (even at the expense of some performance).
